03/02/2004
ATHENS, Greece -- The defence ministry said Monday (2 February) that 10,000 army, navy and air force personnel would become directly involved in security arrangements for the Summer Olympics. 
The soldiers would join 41,000 police, firefighters and members of the coast guard in protecting Olympic venues and athletes. 
Defence Minister Yiannos Papantoniou said the major political parties have agreed to allow the military to become involved in domestic security operations, an area which had been off-limits to the army until now.
In other news Monday, officials from the Bureau International des Expositions arrived in Thessaloniki to examine the city's bid to host the 2008 World Expo. 
Alternate Foreign Minister Tassos Giannitsis assured them the infrastructure could handle major events. 
(AP, MPA - 02/02/04)
